Task 1: Configure a Secure VM Environment
Subtask 1.1: System Update and Security Hardening
First, we need to ensure our system is up-to-date and properly secured for investigation work.

Step 1: Open the terminal by pressing Ctrl + Alt + T or clicking on the terminal icon in the taskbar.

Step 2: Update the system package repository and upgrade all packages:

sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
Step 3: Install essential security tools and dependencies:

sudo apt install -y curl wget git vim ufw fail2ban htop tree unzip
Step 4: Configure the firewall for basic protection:

# Enable UFW firewall
sudo ufw enable

# Set default policies
sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw default allow outgoing

# Allow SSH (if needed for remote access)
sudo ufw allow ssh

# Check firewall status
sudo ufw status verbose
Subtask 1.2: Create Dedicated Investigation User
Step 1: Create a dedicated user account for investigation activities:

sudo adduser investigator
When prompted, enter a strong password and fill in the user information.

Step 2: Add the investigator user to necessary groups:

sudo usermod -aG sudo investigator
Step 3: Switch to the investigator user:

su - investigator
Subtask 1.3: Configure System for Privacy
Step 1: Disable system logging for enhanced privacy:

# Create a script to manage logging
cat << 'EOF' > ~/disable_logs.sh
#!/bin/bash
# Disable various system logs
sudo systemctl stop rsyslog
sudo systemctl disable rsyslog
sudo systemctl stop systemd-journald
sudo rm -rf /var/log/*
echo "System logging disabled for privacy"
EOF

chmod +x ~/disable_logs.sh
Step 2: Configure DNS for privacy:

# Backup original DNS configuration
sudo cp /etc/systemd/resolved.conf /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.backup

# Configure privacy-focused DNS
sudo tee /etc/systemd/resolved.conf << EOF
[Resolve]
DNS=1.1.1.1 9.9.9.9
FallbackDNS=8.8.8.8 8.8.4.4
DNSSEC=yes
DNSOverTLS=yes
EOF

# Restart DNS resolver
sudo systemctl restart systemd-resolved
Task 2: Install Tor and Tails for Secure Browsing
Subtask 2.1: Install Tor Browser
Step 1: Download the official Tor Browser:

cd ~/Downloads
wget https://www.torproject.org/dist/torbrowser/13.0.8/tor-browser-linux64-13.0.8_ALL.tar.xz
Step 2: Verify the download and extract:

# Extract Tor Browser
tar -xf tor-browser-linux64-13.0.8_ALL.tar.xz

# Move to applications directory
sudo mv tor-browser_en-US /opt/tor-browser

# Create symbolic link for easy access
sudo ln -sf /opt/tor-browser/Browser/start-tor-browser /usr/local/bin/tor-browser
Step 3: Create a desktop launcher:

cat << 'EOF' > ~/.local/share/applications/tor-browser.desktop
[Desktop Entry]
Name=Tor Browser
Comment=Anonymous web browsing
Exec=/opt/tor-browser/Browser/start-tor-browser
Icon=/opt/tor-browser/Browser/browser/chrome/icons/default/default128.png
Type=Application
Categories=Network;WebBrowser;
EOF
Step 4: Test Tor Browser installation:

tor-browser &
Subtask 2.2: Configure Tor Service
Step 1: Install Tor service for system-wide proxy:

sudo apt install -y tor
Step 2: Configure Tor service:

# Backup original configuration
sudo cp /etc/tor/torrc /etc/tor/torrc.backup

# Create custom Tor configuration
sudo tee /etc/tor/torrc << 'EOF'
# Basic Tor configuration for OSINT
SocksPort 9050
ControlPort 9051
CookieAuthentication 1
DataDirectory /var/lib/tor

# Enhanced privacy settings
ExitPolicy reject *:*
ClientOnly 1
SafeLogging 1

# Circuit configuration
NewCircuitPeriod 30
MaxCircuitDirtiness 600
CircuitBuildTimeout 60

# Entry guards
NumEntryGuards 3
EOF
Step 3: Start and enable Tor service:

sudo systemctl start tor
sudo systemctl enable tor
sudo systemctl status tor
Subtask 2.3: Set Up Tails USB (Virtual Environment)
Since we're working in a cloud environment, we'll create a Tails-like secure environment.

Step 1: Create a secure workspace directory:

mkdir -p ~/tails-workspace
cd ~/tails-workspace
Step 2: Install Tails-like security tools:

# Install amnesia tools
sudo apt install -y secure-delete bleachbit mat2

# Create secure deletion script
cat << 'EOF' > ~/secure_delete.sh
#!/bin/bash
# Secure deletion script similar to Tails
if [ $# -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "Usage: $0 <file_or_directory>"
    exit 1
fi

echo "Securely deleting: $1"
shred -vfz -n 3 "$1" 2>/dev/null || srm -r "$1" 2>/dev/null || rm -rf "$1"
echo "Deletion complete"
EOF

chmod +x ~/secure_delete.sh
Step 3: Configure memory protection:

# Create RAM disk for temporary files
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/ramdisk
echo "tmpfs /mnt/ramdisk tmpfs defaults,size=1G,noatime,mode=1777 0 0" | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
sudo mount -a

# Create alias for secure workspace
echo "alias secure-work='cd /mnt/ramdisk'" >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc
Task 3: Set Up Proxychains and OPSEC Toolkits
Subtask 3.1: Install and Configure Proxychains
Step 1: Install proxychains:

sudo apt install -y proxychains4
Step 2: Configure proxychains for Tor:

# Backup original configuration
sudo cp /etc/proxychains4.conf /etc/proxychains4.conf.backup

# Create custom proxychains configuration
sudo tee /etc/proxychains4.conf << 'EOF'
# Proxychains configuration for OSINT investigations
strict_chain
proxy_dns
remote_dns_subnet 224
tcp_read_time_out 15000
tcp_connect_time_out 8000
localnet 127.0.0.0/255.0.0.0
localnet 10.0.0.0/255.0.0.0
localnet 172.16.0.0/255.240.0.0
localnet 192.168.0.0/255.255.0.0

[ProxyList]
socks5 127.0.0.1 9050
EOF
Step 3: Test proxychains configuration:

# Test with curl
proxychains4 curl -s https://check.torproject.org/api/ip

# Test with wget
proxychains4 wget -qO- https://ipinfo.io/ip
